Prints what the device tree says about configuration space before anything maps
it. The question it answers is the RISC-V half of the x86_64 firmware report:
the board has no architectural address for a bus, so either the tree names one
or the kernel is guessing, and a guess would map a window over whatever else
lives at that address.

Observed on QEMU 8.x `-machine virt -bios default`:

    MOLT_FDT: Some(Region { base: 30000000, size: 10000000 })

That is 256 MiB, so 256 buses of 1 MiB each, which is what `Ecam::span(0, 255)`
then asks `open_window` to map — and 0x3000_0000 is outside every region the
memory map reports, so `Inventory::device` classifies it as a hole and the
window comes back `Cache::Device` rather than write-back.

Worth noting for anyone reading `paging.rs` next to this: 0x3000_0000 is also
the *virtual* address the UART window uses. The two never collide, because on
RISC-V only RAM and the image are identity mapped and every device window is
handed a virtual address from 0x4_0000_0000 upward.

Apply with `git apply experiments/riscv-device-tree-report.patch`, run
`cargo smoke riscv64`, then revert.

--- a/crates/platforms/riscv/src/lib.rs
+++ b/crates/platforms/riscv/src/lib.rs
@@ fn initialize
             let _ = writeln!(SerialWriter::new(&mut self.serial), "MOLT_SBI_CONSOLE: {console:?}");

+            let _ = writeln!(SerialWriter::new(&mut self.serial), "MOLT_FDT: {:x?}", self.bus);
             trap::init();
